courses.learning_outcomes:
• define and describe the basic steps and issues in the production of historical knowledge and Historiography;
• recognise the ways that philosophies and theories of history have shaped the ways that we understand processes of social change;
• demonstrate through practice the fundamental analytical skills necessary to effectively read and comprehend historical documents;
• be aware of the basic methodological issues in historical-comparative analysis;
• develop critical and reflexive skills in appraising historical-comparative works; and
• appreciate the values of historical-comparative analysis.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to :
1. state the purposes and the key features of ethnographic study ;
2. understand the role of the researcher & the ethics in ethnographic study ;
3. explain the procedures for data collection of ethnographic study in education ;
4. apply the ethnographic methods to design an educational research.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
• Appreciate the complexity of real life in school;
• Develop an integrative perspective about organizational life in school;
• Become an independent and critical thinker;
• Employ organizational theory as a lens to interpret everyday organizational life;
• Apply theories to improve organizational practice;
• Explore management practices across cultural boundaries;
• Understand the new roles emerging in organizations as a result of innovations in technology.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completing this course, students are expected to
1. Understand the importance of curriculum design in relation to teaching and student learning;
2. Grasp the main elements of curriculum development and their alignment;
3. Be able to design, implement, and evaluate a curriculum;
4. Be better equipped to critique curriculum policies and reforms;
5. Have a global curriculum consciousness at both theoretical and practical levels.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
1. state the purposes of curriculum evaluation;
2. identify the essential criteria for evaluating the quality of a curriculum;
3. explain the differences between evaluation of the implemented curriculum and evaluation of the learned curriculum;
4. analyze the strengths and weaknesses of various evaluation designs;
5. conduct meta-evaluations;
6. plan a comprehensive evaluation to judge the quality and effectiveness of a curriculum.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

At the end of this course, students are expected:
1. to become familiar with the basic theories of curriculum change and implementation;
2. to acquire the practical skills of and understand approaches to managing curriculum change;
3. to present briefly their ideas on important issues and trends of curriculum change and implementation in Chinese societies; and
4. to examine critically a number of current issues related to curriculum change and implementation in Chinese societies.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

courses.course_syllabus:
• The need for educational change;
• Curriculum reforms in Chinese societies and other countries;
• Globalization and educational reform;
• Policy attribute theory and characteristics of curriculum change;
• The bottleneck effect and the interaction between policy, people and place;
• Teacher change: Beliefs, attitudes, concerns and emotion;
• School-based curriculum development and professional learning communities;
• Change leadership and school culture.

(For reference only, please refer to the course outline of respective teacher for details.)

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:

1. explain, supported with examples, the notion, scope, and importance of language awareness in English Language education;
2. elucidate current conceptions of English as an international language as they relate to English Language education;
3. provide examples to illustrate the dynamic relationships between subject content knowledge and pedagogical content knowledge in the area of English Language education;
4. design effective language awareness tasks and lessons for students; and
5. make informed judgements when evaluating the language found in commercially-produced learning resources.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
1. describe the goals of science education;
2. analyze the major factors affecting science curriculum development in Hong Kong;
3. identify the essential criteria for selecting and organizing the contents in a science curriculum;
4. explain why science teachers should consider various approaches (e.g. STS) to curriculum planning;
5. incorporate the nature of science, scientific inquiry, unifying concepts/ crosscutting concepts, project-based approach appropriately into the science curricula;
6. understand the rationales and some common practices in the school-based curriculum development in science subjects;
7. know the recent development of some science curricula in China and other countries;
8. address student diversity in science curricula;
9. describe and explain the effect of language and gender on science learning outcomes;
10. realize the significance of affective dimension in curriculum development and suggest teaching strategies to improve affective learning outcomes in science.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, participants will be able to:
1. describe the differences and similarities of some major theories concerning the learning of science;
2. apply various methods to elicit and analyze students’ prior knowledge;
3. design relevant instructional strategies for effecting conceptual change;
4. use appropriate forms of practical work for achieve targeted outcomes;
5. maintain extended dialogue with students for the construction of science concepts;
6. explain why assessment reform is needed in science education in Hong Kong;
7. construct effective assessment items and tasks for school science;
8. analyze the pros and cons of school-based assessment for school science.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

This course aims to provide learning opportunities for participants to:
1. better understand the complexity of curriculum decision-making at various levels;
2. better identify the relationship of what, who, how and why in curriculum decisions;
3. use intellectual tools and resources to better represent their understanding of decision-making at various levels;
4. comment critically on the politics embedded in the local and global curriculum decision cases;
5. become more consciously aware of their own curriculum decision-making dynamics.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

At the end of the course, students should be able to
1. identify major issues related to the development of humanities curriculum in local and comparative perspectives;
2. develop a deeper understanding of the relationship between research literature and local experiences;
3. grasp a basic idea of dialectical reading of research literature from a practitioner’s perspective.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After this course, students should be able to:

1. understand the rationales and learning theories (e.g. situated learning, distributed cognition) behind the application of digital technologies in education;
2. identify and select digital technology-enhanced learning and teaching approaches appropriate for specific educational goals

and pedagogical contexts;
3. gain technological knowledge and skills for leveraging digital technology-enhanced pedagogies in different educational settings;
4. demonstrate awareness of emerging digital technologies and their potential for pedagogical use.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After the course, participants will be able to
1. Better understand the complexity of the school organization and the dynamics of organizational change;
2. Build a greater connection between participants’ personal leadership and organizational effectiveness;
3. Develop a greater sense of self-awareness in leading and managing effective organizational changes in schools;
4. Improve participants’ own work and the work of teams that the participants’ are leading; and
5. Create greater competitiveness through the practice of the disciplines of organizational learning.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of the course, participants are able to

• Demonstrate a better understanding of the evolution and concept of professional learning communities (PLCs);
• Demonstrate a better understanding of the various approaches and constructs of professional development in enhancing personal and organizational capacity building;
• Understand and demonstrate the good practices and critical factors leading to the successful building of professional learning communities in Hong Kong schools;
• Analyse and reflect on the features of professional learning systems in their own school;
• Grasp the skills to help improve/ develop their own development programs or PLCs in school.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

1. Appreciate the social and political backgrounds behind an educational policy or issue;
2. Examine educational policies or issues using one or more sociological approaches;;
3. Understand the internal logic and functions within an educational institution;
4. Develop competence in group problem solving when analyzing school problems;
5. Apply knowledge of school management and leadership to identify core issues in school problems and to propose viable solutions to deal with these problems;
6. Express personal vision of committing to the causes of maximizing human potential and preserving human values and integrity.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

1. Understand fundamental concepts and theories relevant to the relationship between education policy and its societal contexts;
2. Develop understanding on how historical and societal contexts influenced modern schooling systems and policies;
3. Critically analyze how education policies affect structure and development of modern societies;
4. Extend knowledge to identify and discuss functions and effects of modern education policies in addressing social issues in modern society

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After the course, students will be able:
1. To delineate the domestic and international contexts of development;
2. To identify and analyze educational policies and reforms in addressing issues in development;
3. To examine interactions between education and development from a multidisciplinary perspectives.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

On completion of the course, students will be able:
1) to identify and examine the major theoretical concerns in the planning and finance of education;
2) to apply the skills of manpower projection in the development of education, for different levels and types of education;
3) to identify and explain the major economic concepts relevant to the planning and finance of education;
4) to delineate the effects on efficiency and social equity of resources mobilization and allocation in educational planning and finance at the different levels.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

To enable participants to
1. develop an understanding of advanced quantitative analysis in classroom & school settings;
2. critique the strengths and weaknesses of various statistical methods;
3. identify appropriate quantitative techniques to problems regularly encountered in classroom and school settings; and
4. conduct quantitative analyses and provide accurate interpretation of the outputs.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:
1. state the strength of structural equation modeling as compared to traditional ANOVA and regression approaches;
2. conduct confirmatory factor analyses on instruments;
3. conduct analyses on simple full models using structural equation modeling;
4. compare and select models using goodness of fit indexes and other evaluation criteria; and
5. revise models according to fit and parameter statistics.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
1. know about action research as a cyclic process of inquiry and its purposes of undertaking in the field of education;
2. improve their ability to read, write, and act reflectively, critically and analytically as drawn from the interpretative perspective;
3. describe the principles of action research;
4. be aware of the importance and relevance of research ethics;
5. be able to design and construct their own action plans in accordance with the action research principles.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After the study of this course, students should be able to:
1. Identify and define a learning problem/ issue for investigation;
2. Conduct focused literature review that informs the design and evaluation of a technology-enhanced learning environment
(or other technology-enhanced educational “products”) geared towards addressing the identified learning problem/ issue;
3. Formulate an adequate research approach to accomplishing a theoretically informed and empirically grounded learning
design study;
4. Sharpen their collaborative skills and appreciate the power of collective intelligence.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. Identify and define a significant and meaningful problem or issue related to education for investigation;
2. Conduct focused literature review and formulate adequate research to enrich their understanding on the identified problem/issue in education;
3. Enhance their collaborative and research skills.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By completing this course, students will be able to
1. demonstrate teaching competence;
2. integrate and apply pedagogical and content knowledge into classroom practice;
3. develop appropriate values as a qualified teacher.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After completing this course students should be able to:
• Better understand the antecedents and prevalence of various social phenomena, and their effects on students’ psychological functioning;
• Describe and discuss the risk and protective factors associated with various contemporary issues in students’ personal and social development;
• Describe and discuss the methods used by researchers to study students’ personal and social development;
• Critique contemporary issues in students’ personal and social development;
• Identify ways to protect students from unhealthy influences in the society and support their personal and social development.
• Form firm opinions on a variety of contemporary issues and offer evidence-based arguments for their positions through written assignments.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, you will be able to:

• Describe the major theories and empirical findings in the field of achievement motivation;
• Better understand the learning experience of students from diverse backgrounds, and the influence of the social context on their motivation;
• Describe and discuss the methods used by researchers to study achievement motivation;
• Conduct simple, systematic investigations of your students' motivation;
• Critique common teaching strategies and identify ways to support students' learning.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

