courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon satisfactory completion of the course, students will have:
1. a basic understanding of the fundamental elements of counselling skills;
2. a good understanding of a range of counselling theories;
3. a basic understanding of different psychotherapeutic interventions;
4. the ability to understand a person using different theoretical counselling frameworks;
5. the ability to compare and contrast different theories critically;
6. experiential knowledge of introspection through in-class activities

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon completion of this course, students should be able to:
1. demonstrate a good understanding of the concept of higher order thinking skills and its component concepts;
2. evaluate the impact of instructional design and strategies on the use of higher order thinking skills;
3. apply some effective and evidence-based instructional design and strategies for fostering the use of higher order thinking skills in schools and other educational settings.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

After the course, students will be able to:
1. acquired understanding of family influence and parents’ role on children education;
2. apply the knowledge of the logic of parental involvement to enhance FSC collaboration;
3. acquired practical strategies to initiate and improve FSC collaboration;
4. acquired knowledge to understand research on FSC collaboration with different methods;
5. develop awareness of ways to manage students’ learning issues through FSC collaboration

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
• Describe the major sociological understanding and related empirical evidence on childhood, motherhood, and parent-child relationship;
• Better understand parenting practices against different social, cultural, and historical contexts;
• Critique contemporary issues in parenting;
• Understand the implications of parenting for social inequality and social development.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

courses.course_syllabus:
The nature and definitions of teaching;
Teaching models and approaches;
Applying learning theories to instructional design;
Behaviorism, cognitivism, constructivism, and humanism in instructional design;
Catering for individual difference;
Effective teaching.
Paradigms of research on teaching and teachers.

(For reference only, please refer to the course outline of respective teacher for details.)

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to

1. identify the basic concept in curriculum organization;
2. specify the relationship between curriculum organization and curriculum development;
3. distinguish the peculiar features associated with a range of curriculum organization approaches;
4. articulate the strengths and weaknesses of various curriculum organization approaches;
5. recognize the decision-making features associated with curriculum organization;
6. critically analyze controversial issues relating to curriculum organization.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

courses.course_syllabus:
• Curriculum and curriculum inquiry;
• Curriculum paradigms;
• Traditionalism/ conceptual-empiricism/ reconceptualism, and perennial analytic/ practical inquiry/ critical praxis paradigm;
• Paradigmatic curriculum inquiry on various issues including hidden curriculum, teacher emotion, student assessment, and orientations of curriculum implementation;
• Forms of curriculum inquiry;
• Quantitative, qualitative and mixed-methods design in curriculum inquiry;
• Trends of curriculum inquiry.

(For reference only, please refer to the course outline of respective teacher for details.)

courses.learning_outcomes:
On completing the course, students are expected to be able:
1. to examine the major contextual forces shaping school reform;
2. to investigate the dynamics of school reform;
3. to analyze the impact of school reform policies on the local educational landscape;
4. to present reasoned and coherent arguments for the pros and cons of a reform issue of choice.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

1. Gained a better understanding of the theoretical development in the field of educational organisation and leadership;
2. Critically examined the methodological issues in educational leadership;
3. Thought through a set of questions aimed at helping you develop a worthwhile research proposal;
4. Worked closely with your classmates to understand and to improve your understanding of the literature in educational organization and leadership in general, and of your focused area in particular; and

5. Had the opportunity to support and critique classmates’ work and had them done the same for you.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

At the end of the course, students should be able to:
1. develop an in-depth understanding of advanced quantitative analysis in educational settings;
2. critique the strengths and weaknesses of various advanced methods as applied in real empirical studies;
3. identify appropriate advanced quantitative techniques to problems regularly encountered in school and educational settings; and
4. conduct advanced quantitative analyses and provide accurate interpretation of the findings.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)

Upon satisfactory completion of the course, students are expected to be able to:
1. gain familiarity with the current literature on the psychological development and needs of school-age children and adolescents, and on counseling and guidance interventions in schools settings, including those related to comprehensive school guidance;
2. point out relevant conceptual frameworks in the psychological literature that could be used to guide school guidance and counseling service in Hong Kong school settings;
3. describe and comment on models related to the organization, implementation, and evaluation of comprehensive school guidance and counseling activities in school settings; and
4. understand the importance and role of preventive, developmental, and remedial interventions in school settings, and propose ways that these interventions could be developed, implemented and evaluated.

(Individual course teachers may update the learning outcome as and whenever necessary.)
